Great spot for casual brunch and coffee/tea with a friend when in Old Towne! The atmosphere is very open and white, with wooden counters and a back area for more seats. However, I usually sit on the bar counter next to the register.

All of our food was delicious, and the ruben ("Catcher in the Rye") and italian sandwiches were the best we've ever had! The service was impeccable, and we enjoyed  their patio seating with a warm fire pit.

They have every tea imaginable.   Their pastries are great especially the in-house ones.   Try the banana chocolate bread or the pumpkin chocolate bread if they haven't run out of it. Their food is great too.   On the weekends,  there are wood fires in the fire pit and the chiminea.  They have afternoon sun and one table is protected from rain. It took a second for them to take my order because of switching over the drawers, but I’ve worked in food service before and was more than happy to wait!  I liked the veggie selection on the Veggie Panini— though the focaccia was soggy :/ (seen in photo). I would’ve liked more of a “crunch” when eating it. I think the panini press may have pressed more liquid into the bread from the veggies than expected. Other than the bread, I liked the savory taste and variety of sandwiches they had. I’ll definitely be coming back to try the drinks!  I read some comments on here about it not being trans-friendly and, as a trans person, treaded with caution. However, I wasn’t gendered at all, which was lovely! Happy to know this experience with their staff included gender-neutral language. It’s a tough world out there for trans folks, and so this was reassuring.  Can’t wait to return!

Not trans friendly. When they went to bring me my order they shouted my legal name on my credit card to the whole room. This is jarring and embarrassing as some of my friends only know me by my preferred name. And I was presenting as the opposite gender of the name on my card.  Any other coffee shop I’ve been to asks for a name on the order. I even heard the cashier ask for other people’s names, but not mine. It may have been an honest mistake, but at the very least, this was insensitive.  On top of all this, the food was way over priced. Most definitely not returning here.  Edit: Wow. I just wanted to add a response to the owner. Changing your name legally is an incredibly expensive, time consuming process. I have started this myself, but not all trans folks have those resources available. It would be incredibly accommodating and little effort to your business to just ask card customers what they’re name is. Every other coffee shop I’ve been to in Chicago asks my name even if I pay with card.

I usually avoid writing negative reviews but after several years of bad experiences at BP I am choosing to submit my criticism in hope that can make some improvements. Hi, former employee here! I can’t stress enough how absolutely awful this place is. I’m all about shopping small and supporting local businesses, but the Bourgeois Pig is not worth your time or money. The owner can’t properly manage his inventory or his finances, constantly running out of multiple ingredients for both the kitchen and coffee bar; he also frequently bounces employees’ paychecks, causing them to go several weeks to even months unpaid. The prices here would make you think you’re getting high-quality food, but spoiler alert: If it’s in stock at all, it’s probably because someone grabbed it from the CVS down the street. Most of the food is reheated in the microwave; nothing is made to order, aside from the sandwiches (if you can get one!). The kitchen staff is often unable to make half (or more) of the menu due to the lack of ingredients. I mean, what kind of coffee shop can’t even keep coffee in stock? The facility is a dump; nothing is ever properly sanitized or cleaned, and I can only imagine what the health department would have to say about the condition of their food prep area. On one occasion, I was grinding coffee and some of it sprayed out of the grinder onto the counter (because the grinder was probably older than I am), and when I went to sweep it into the garbage can, I was instructed not to waste product and put it back in the coffee machine instead. The owner was (and probably still is) in so much debt with the towel sanitizing company that we had to “wash” the towels we used to clean kitchen equipment ourselves by soaking them overnight in buckets of water. He also treats his employees like garbage and creates an extremely stressful environment. I could go on, but I’d hope this has been enough to encourage you to take your business elsewhere.

I have ordered from Bourgeois Pig a few times and had good experiences before today. I ordered the Salade Nicoise for delivery at work and was surprised that the hard boiled eggs, bread, and dressing were missing. I had also requested no anchovies and was given anchovies. I called the Cafe to explain and I was told that the menu is very “hit or miss” “we do the best that we can” I was also told they didn’t have those ingredients today which is why they were missing on my salad. I explained that it would have been nice to know as I would have ordered something different. Again I was told the menu is very hit or miss and they do the best they can. I asked for some sort of credit for next time and I was also told that was not an option. Needless to say this is my first ever review on a restaurant. The customer service was shocking.

Seemed like an awesome place to do some work on a laptop or catch up with a friend. I will definitely be making a stop next time I'm in Lincoln Park!

Great cup of coffee in a gorgeous setting. Seating for folks looking to chat and catch up or work on laptops. There is free WiFi.

Had a really good cup of coffee, and my wife and I had two of their sandwiches. Both were delicious, and highly recommend. The issue lies with the service... My favorite Cafe in the city!

I used to work here until I finally quit - the owner Mason doesn't pay his employees on time, ever and it has been like that for at least a year. It had taken me 2 months to get one of my checks because there was not enough money in his account to pay me. Others I'd have to wait weeks. Some people that worked here didn't even get paid for the proper amount of hours that they worked. Do not support this extremely selfish and poorly managed business. Also, working here was hell, as we always ran out of everything and would have to improvise what to tell customers. There were multiple times when we had literally run out of coffee beans. I cannot stress enough that this place is a dump and treats its employees terribly. Also, I would love to see what a health inspector would have to say about this place. Do not support.
Ordered from this place off uber eats and was a complete scam. My sandwich came with nothing described on the menu. Do NOT waste your money here. I tried calling several times and no one picked up.
This is easily in my top two favorite coffee shops in Chicago.

If I could give negative stars I would. This place has garbage service. We waited in line for 20 minutes because we heard this place was great. And then after ordering waited another 15 minutes while the barista made drinks for other people. Did we get a damn apology? NOPE. Do not waste your time on this horrible place.

ok so I have to admit, I came here cos I had a craving. I decided to meet M and she was at DePaul at the time. She recommended this place, and some others, I tried it based on its name and the fact that it had waffles.  I had been craving waffles for a month, but my waistline needed nothing more than broccoli soup and green beans. Mind over matter, I went to La Pig. I loved it.  The place itself looks like an old house thats been renovated. Both downstairs and upstairs have wooden tables and chairs, but upstairs has old victorian seating as well- a chaise, and chairs made of purple chintz. Never thought I would see that outside England. Love the kitsch artwork on the walls as well.  My waffle was AMAZING. I had nutella and honey on mine and it remained crisp till the end, even though I took 2 hours to eat it. And I ate the whole thing too. M had the italian sandwich, which was pretty good, but I would really recommend the waffle :)
Best sandwich place around, and the coffee isn't bad either :)
Nice environment; sandwiches are fine but nothing special

Great vibe, nice amd cozy location, must visit!

Best sandwich I have ever had - a must have for anyone visiting or living in the city

I've watched this place slowly go downhill while I was in school at DePaul, and even after graduation it hasn't quite come back.  Their hours fluctuated wildly, from being open until 10ish when I was a freshman, to closing at 6, to being 7-7 everyday now. The coffee is almost always burnt, but not undrinkable. The sandwiches are pretty good, depending on what you get, but overpriced. The space is big, but goofily laid out.  I get the sense they just don't know what to do with it. It used to be that drinks were on one side and food on the other, but there have been so many changes made in the past few years I can't keep up.  The ambiance is nice, and it's a good place to meet and get something done. I keep coming back, clearly, hoping it's become everything I want it to be. And maybe it will one day.
Got filtered coffee instead when asked for latte. Probably the worst coffee I ever had. Also not a nice Chai tea. Not good guys!
Great place to visit, eat a delicious breakfast bowl, grab a chai caramel candy and read a cool novel with a latte!

So disappointed! I always pass by and have been meaning to try it. The coffee was bitter and not fully hot. We ordered a sandwhich and a scrambled egg bowl. I didn't even try the potatoes because they looked dry, cold and nasty. We didn't have a good experience at all.

I was excited to go here for the first time with my friends one morning.  I had walked by every day on my way home from work and it looked like a nice and comfortable place to have coffee.  We arrived after open and walked in.  Both workers ignored us so we asked if they were open and they said "sort of".  We offered to come back in a few minutes but again, we were ignored. After sitting at a table for five minutes we decided to leave and try another coffee shop down the street.  Worst customer service I've ever experienced.
